b"\xe2\x80\x9cWhen I was younger, my father used to buy us black greeting cards. At the time, I thought they were super corny but without fail, on every major holiday, he would give them to us with a black image gracing the cover and a message on the inside that I could relate to. The cards were sold at an independent black bookstore that closed down shortly after my mother moved us to California. I never forgot those cards or the way they made me feel growing up.

Since having my son, I've had a burning itch to bring those feelings back so that I could share them with him. The urge of wanting to recreate that and (re)inspire others with positive and relatable images of black people eventually overcame me.

While filling a void, I decided to spawn a personality that people could relate to; a voice that is honest, refreshing and real. I'm using advice and motivating/inspiring quotes that were offered to me. Even some of the influential people I meet will be written in this journey. Ultimately, this is the world illustrated and narrated by me.\xe2\x80\x9d - @bymsjames"

b'Proudly\xc2\xa0presenting our celebration of Juneteenth. 
June 19th, 1865 is popularly recognized as Juneteenth. This holiday commemorates the day when Black Americans in the last of the Confederate States (Texas), were notified of both the end of the civil war and slavery. 
Though Black Americans were legally freed when the Emancipation Proclamation was issued in 1863 by president Abrahamn Lincoln, it took over 2 years for word to spread through the South. 
In honor of Juneteenth, we will be highlighting Black creatives and small businesses. Swipe to see who we are celebrating with!'

b'In 2019 we met under the worst of conditions. As a company, we decided to not just apologize, but to deal with the situation head-on with open dialogue, and to learn from the experience. To do better as a brand. Project Level and Forever 21 began direct and meaningful talks, and over the course of a year we listened. We worked hard to give this story an ending that would result in equity and entrepreneurship.

This forthcoming collaboration is designed by the youth of Project Level, from apparel to marketing. While we mentored and gave them an opportunity to showcase their skills, @projectlevel gave us the gift of change. Coming 7/30.

Tomorrow we celebrate #Juneteenth. Stay tuned... #f21xprojectlevel'

b'Over the past few days, we\xe2\x80\x99ve had open dialogue amongst our F21 Family on how we can make a change together.

2020 has been a tough year for many including our company. As you may know, we are working on strengthening our financial positioning but we are fully committed to standing up for what is right.

Here are the steps we are taking today to make an immediate impact in supporting our black employees and communities as we continue to determine our long term goals. We are committed to:

1. Forming a F21 Diversity Committee to lead and develop inclusivity initiatives to continue to evolve our long term cultural change.

2. Creating clear goals for equal opportunities in our workplace and across our content channels to lift up our black community.

3. Having more black representation in our management and leadership teams throughout our organization.

4. To providing a platform to better represent the black community through collaboration and storytelling with black creators and models.

5. Supporting and collaborating with black owned fashion and beauty brands.

We recognize that this is not a short term problem. This is a long term goal that we want to be transparent with you about. So, we will be posting updates on our site and page as our initiatives progress.

#blacklivesmatter'

b'Thank you to everybody who has shared feedback and concern. Your voices are extremely important to us and we are sorry that we did not share this sooner. We\xe2\x80\x99ve taken the last few days to stay silent to regroup, listen and educate ourselves on how we can do better to contribute to our communities.

Like so many of you, we have been deeply saddened and angered by recent events in our country. We feel your pain and outrage, and understand you want to see meaningful change. No words or social posts will convey this change, we know we must take action, not just today but everyday going forward. We are currently planning with our partners and community leaders on how we can help and will be sharing that information as soon as possible.

It starts with us listening to our employees, our customers and communities as they all share what it\xe2\x80\x99s like to be a person of color in our country today. Our company values diversity and inclusion above all, and we are devoted to starting new conversations, listening intently, and most importantly learning from you.

Many of you have shared your thoughts and we want you to know we\xe2\x80\x99re listening. As a brand we know we must do more and we are fully invested in taking the actions necessary. We know we still have a ways to go but TOGETHER we can make a difference.

#blacklivesmatter'

b'This is a very painful time. We have been deeply heartbroken over the recent events in our country. 
The Forever 21 family stands in solidarity with you. We are not just a clothing brand. We are real people and a community. We feel your pain and outrage, and understand you want to see meaningful change. 
Together we can make a difference, not just today but everyday.

#forevertogether'
